<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1913-12-29T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1913-12-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="1603" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1603">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.93/59.</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">Vice Consul <persName type="from">Guyant</persName> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss>.</hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#left">No. 289.]</seg>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">American Consulate</hi>, <lb/>
                                        <hi rend="italic">Ensenada</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1913-12-29">
                                        <hi rend="italic">December 29, 1913</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: With reference to the general subject
                                of assistance to Chinese in Mexico by American Consular officers, I
                                have the honor to transmit herewith a list of the Chinese firms in
                                Ensenada showing a close estimate of the present value of stocks of
                                merchandise on hand expressed in Mexican currency.<note n="156" xml:id="d1603fn156">Not printed.</note>
                            </p>
                            <p>From this statement it will be noted that the Chinese have
                                merchandise here to the value of about $100,000, American money.
                                This estimate does not include cash on hand.</p>
                            <p>The general fear among local merchants that the Governor will soon
                                commence making forced loans of money and supplies for the soldiers
                                has led the Chinese merchants to make a formal request for the
                                protection of this Consulate.</p>
                            <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Claude E. Guyant</hi></signed>.</closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>